ballistic missile.

12:03.623 --> 12:06.159 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, there's a lot of guesswork
involved.

12:06.192 --> 12:11.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think it's fair to say
that, at this
point, the North Koreans may
have the about

12:11.297 --> 12:18.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to put a nuclear warhead on a
medium-range
ballistic missile, and that
missile could

12:18.972 --> 12:21.541 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hit Japan, it could hit South
Korea.

12:21.574 --> 12:28.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they are probably that far,
according
to what we hear from South Korea
and U.S.

12:28.147 --> 12:29.949 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
intelligence sources.

12:29.983 --> 12:34.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Gary Samore, what
are the North
Koreans trying to say with this
test, do you

12:34.320 --> 12:36.055 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
believe?

12:36.089 --> 12:38.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GARY SAMORE, Former Presidential
Adviser on
Arms Control: Well, of course,
the specific

12:38.491 --> 12:46.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
timing was to celebrate the 68th
anniversary
of the foundation of North
Korea.

12:46.165 --> 12:51.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think, more broadly, I
think Kim Jong-un
is determined to demonstrate
that he is not

12:51.070 --> 12:57.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to be cowed or deterred by
U.N. Security
Council injunctions and the
threat of sanctions,

12:57.910 --> 13:02.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which are demanding the he halt
testing and
eventually give up his nuclear
weapons program.

13:02.882 --> 13:08.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I believe the North Koreans
are trying
to make it clear to the Security
Council and

13:08.121 --> 13:13.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the big powers, especially
China and the
U.S., that they are determined
to retain and

13:13.159 --> 13:15.261 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
expand their nuclear weapons
capability.

13:15.294 --> 13:20.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Greg Thielmann,
does this represent
a failure of American policy,
policy of the

13:20.266 --> 13:22.235 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
rest the world toward North
Korea?

13:22.268 --> 13:27.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GREG THIELMANN: Well, I think,
almost by definition,
it represents a failure, since
the objective

13:27.273 --> 13:33.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that almost all countries in the
world agree
to which is not to expand the
number of countries

13:33.946 --> 13:37.650 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that possess nuclear attack
capability.

13:37.684 --> 13:43.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So -- but what's
been wrong
about that policy?

13:43.289 --> 13:44.323 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Has it been too tough?

13:44.357 --> 13:45.925 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Has it been too weak?

13:45.958 --> 13:47.860 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How do you size it up?

13:47.894 --> 13:54.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GREG THIELMANN: Well, of course,
U.S. nuclear
nonproliferation policy has
scored some impressive

13:54.400 --> 13:58.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
successes, and I think the Iran
nuclear agreement
of last year is a good example
of that.

13:58.471 --> 14:03.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the case of North Korea, it's
one of the
most difficult of all challenges
we have.

14:04.010 --> 14:10.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there is certainly reason to
criticize
the North Koreans for being bad
negotiating

14:10.817 --> 14:16.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
partners, and they have not been
willing to
carry out some of the
obligations to which

14:16.956 --> 14:18.458 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they have agreed.

14:18.491 --> 14:22.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there are also problems on
the other side
of the table.

14:22.528 --> 14:25.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of the problems we have
right now is,
there is no table.

14:25.498 --> 14:26.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We are not talking to the North
Koreans.

14:26.899 --> 14:28.534 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: There are no
negotiations going.

14:28.568 --> 14:29.535 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GREG THIELMANN: No.

14:29.569 --> 14:31.337 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Let me turn to
Gary Samore.

14:31.370 --> 14:36.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How do you see this question of
flat out that
this means what's been going on
until now

14:36.375 --> 14:37.710 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
has failed?

14:37.744 --> 14:40.713 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GARY SAMORE: Yes, I think that's
right.

14:40.747 --> 14:47.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, going back to President
Reagan, when
we first suspected that North
Korea was pursuing

14:47.086 --> 14:53.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a nuclear weapons program, the
United States
has tried many different ways to
slow down

14:53.259 --> 14:57.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or prevent North Korea from
acquiring nuclear
weapons, including nuclear
diplomacy.

14:57.663 --> 15:03.136 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have had three agreements,
threats of preemptive
war, economic sanctions.

15:03.169 --> 15:07.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have tried many different
methods, and
they have all failed.

15:07.273 --> 15:11.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, as Greg says, it's
an indication
of how difficult this problem
is.

15:11.677 --> 15:17.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have a country that is --
really feels
it has an existential need to
have nuclear

15:17.383 --> 15:23.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
weapons in order to survive, and
the U.S.
options, whether they're
diplomatic, or coercive,

15:23.322 --> 15:26.993 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
or military, are very limited.

15:27.026 --> 15:31.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the question will be whether
or not this
test and North Korea's
continuing defiance

15:31.998 --> 15:37.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will create opportunities, in
particular for
the U.S. and China, to work
together, and

15:37.737 --> 15:42.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that will be seen in the U.N.,
whether or
not the Chinese are prepared to
support additional

15:42.942 --> 15:44.577 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
sanctions measures.

15:44.610 --> 15:47.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let me ask
you about
that, because, up until now, the
U.S., as

15:47.180 --> 15:50.149 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we know, has said there are
preconditions.

15:50.183 --> 15:55.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
North Korea has to meet certain
conditions
before the U.S. will sit down at
the table

15:55.521 --> 15:57.123 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and talk.

15:57.156 --> 15:58.691 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Should that policy go away?

15:58.724 --> 16:01.127 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Should there now be talks
without preconditions?

16:01.160 --> 16:08.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GARY SAMORE: Well, just to be
clear, the U.S.
is prepared to meet with the
North Koreans,

16:08.301 --> 16:11.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with the North Korean diplomats
without any
conditions.

16:11.170 --> 16:16.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The question is, what are the
conditions for
nuclear negotiations, for formal
negotiation?

16:16.609 --> 16:23.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, for me, a minimum condition
has to be
an agreement that the purpose of
nuclear negotiations

16:23.916 --> 16:26.819 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
is to achieve eventual
disarmament.

16:26.853 --> 16:32.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nobody expects that to happen in
the near-term,
but in some kind of sequence,
series of steps,

16:32.158 --> 16:37.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and, secondly, that while the
talks are going
on, North Korean refrain from
nuclear and

16:37.997 --> 16:39.832 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
long-range missile testing.

16:39.866 --> 16:44.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To me, that's a reasonable
minimal requirement,
and I think you could get the
Chinese and

16:44.971 --> 16:48.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the other major powers involved
in the talks
to agree to that.

16:48.407 --> 16:51.711 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, the Obama administration
has been asking
for more.

16:51.744 --> 16:57.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have been asking for
restraints on North
Korean fissile material
destruction as a precondition

16:57.483 --> 16:59.151 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
-- or as a condition for
starting negotiations.

16:59.185 --> 17:00.152 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

17:00.186 --> 17:02.021 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GARY SAMORE: I think that hasn't
worked.

17:02.054 --> 17:07.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think we have to look at
trying to come
to an agreement with China on
conditions that

17:07.960 --> 17:09.095 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
are more realistic.

17:09.128 --> 17:10.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Greg Thielmann,
how do you
see that?

17:10.796 --> 17:12.632 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What do you think needs to
happen now?

17:12.665 --> 17:18.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GREG THIELMANN: I mostly agree
with what Gary
said, but I think that we could
make a mistake

17:18.471 --> 17:25.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in even trying to get North
Korea to go back
to its previous commitment to a
denuclearized

17:25.878 --> 17:27.013 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Korean Peninsula.

17:27.046 --> 17:29.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think, right now, that's
putting the bar
too high.

17:29.548 --> 17:32.618 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We need to negotiate with the
North Koreans.

17:32.652 --> 17:39.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And even if the objective -- the
only objective
we can agree to is a freeze on
North Korean

17:39.158 --> 17:43.129 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nuclear and ballistic missile
testing, I think
that, too, would have value.

17:43.162 --> 17:48.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that doesn't mean we have to
abandon our
objective to ultimately get rid
of all nuclear

17:48.200 --> 17:50.269 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
weapons in the Korean Peninsula.

17:50.303 --> 17:56.409 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But to require the North
Koreans, before entering
negotiation, to accept that as
the ultimate

17:56.442 --> 17:58.911 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
objective of the negotiations I
think is asking
too much.

17:58.945 --> 18:01.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So you're saying,
what, tell
the North Koreans what?

18:01.414 --> 18:03.249 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We will sit down with you --
what?

18:03.282 --> 18:10.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GREG THIELMANN: We will sit down
and negotiate
the terms of a freeze on nuclear
and ballistic

18:10.189 --> 18:12.024 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
missile testing.

18:12.058 --> 18:18.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we will make very clear that
our objective
is to ultimately get rid of all
nuclear weapons

18:18.664 --> 18:22.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the Korean Peninsula, as the
North Koreans
had previously agreed to.

18:22.301 --> 18:25.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Gary Samore, does
that sound
like the right path?

18:25.171 --> 18:29.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GARY SAMORE: Right now, the
North Koreans
are not prepared to talk about
nuclear disarmament,

18:29.909 --> 18:34.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nor are they prepared to accept
any restriction
on their testing activity.

18:34.313 --> 18:39.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And unless you establish, it
seems to me,
a basic premise for the talks,
then -- or

18:39.952 --> 18:43.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the negotiations, then
you're not going
to get anywhere if you don't at
least with

18:43.389 --> 18:44.991 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have an agreement on what it's
all about.

18:45.024 --> 18:48.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, it's a
moment when a
lot of questions are being
asked.

18:48.961 --> 18:52.932 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And we know that it's --
certainly, what North
Korea has done has certainly
gained everyone's

18:52.965 --> 18:54.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
attention.

18:54.367 --> 18:55.668 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Gary Samore, we thank you.

18:55.701 --> 18:56.869 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Greg Thielmann, we thank you.

18:56.902 --> 18:57.870 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GREG THIELMANN: You're welcome.

18:57.903 --> 19:02.942 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GARY SAMORE: Thank you.

19:02.975 --> 19:17.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to our
continuing coverage
of the upcoming 15th anniversary
of the September

19:17.156 --> 19:18.858 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
