country where
the attacks were planned,
Afghanistan.

19:23.529 --> 19:31.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. and NATO deposed the
Taliban government
in the fall of 2001, but 15
years later, American

19:31.504 --> 19:37.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
troops continue to fight and die
there, while
trying to help the Afghans stand
up an army

19:37.510 --> 19:40.046 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to take on a resurgent Taliban.

19:40.079 --> 19:44.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
From Kabul, special
correspondent Jennifer
Glasse reports.

19:44.083 --> 19:50.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: At the Regional
Corps Battle
School in Laghman Province in
Eastern Afghanistan,

19:50.056 --> 19:54.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these Afghan soldiers, many with
years of
battlefield experience, have
been learning

19:54.627 --> 19:57.897 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
leadership skills from coalition
forces.

19:57.930 --> 20:03.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's an Afghan-run school with
U.S. soldiers
and NATO troops serving as
advisers.

20:03.269 --> 20:08.774 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Part of the lesson plan,
U.S.-style military
organization.

20:08.808 --> 20:12.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After completing seven weeks of
training,
these men become noncommissioned
officers,

20:12.812 --> 20:16.749 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a rank that had been exclusive
to the United
States military.

20:16.782 --> 20:18.350 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Adam Weiner is an adviser.

20:18.384 --> 20:19.351 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
2ND.

20:19.385 --> 20:21.220 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
LT.

20:21.253 --> 20:24.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADAM WEINER, Military Adviser:
We have a strong
leadership in the officer and
NCO side, and

20:24.323 --> 20:27.059 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we see the benefits that that
has for our
Army.

20:27.093 --> 20:32.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so we have tried to instill
that into
their training as well to
empower their noncommissioned

20:32.465 --> 20:37.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
officers to take a bigger role
in leading
soldiers alongside their officer
counterparts

20:38.003 --> 20:39.939 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in their units.

20:39.972 --> 20:45.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: Some of these
Afghan soldiers
fought alongside U.S. forces in
Eastern Afghanistan.

20:45.511 --> 20:50.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With only a few American special
forces still
in the country, Afghans must
rely on U.S.

20:50.983 --> 20:53.018 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
airpower when things get tough.

20:53.052 --> 20:59.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): When
the air support
comes, every soldier, every
fighter has better

20:59.725 --> 21:01.026 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
morale.

21:01.060 --> 21:04.497 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are refreshed and fight
with new energy
against the enemy.

21:04.530 --> 21:09.468 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Also, in some districts, there
are high mountains,
and we can not go there.

21:09.502 --> 21:11.871 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So we need the airplanes to
target the enemy.

21:11.904 --> 21:15.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: But after 15
years of U.S.
and coalition efforts on the
ground and least

21:15.674 --> 21:22.114 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
$65 billion, Afghan security
forces are still
a development project.

21:22.148 --> 21:27.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The task of building a military
here didn't
start until 2009, with a
commitment from President

21:27.286 --> 21:32.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obama to do the hard work needed
to help Afghanistan
stand on its own, and reducing
the need for

21:32.691 --> 21:34.827 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
U.S. troops.

21:34.860 --> 21:38.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
General John Nicholson is the
commander of
U.S. and NATO forces in
Afghanistan.

21:38.531 --> 21:43.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's served here before, but now
commands
an international force far
smaller than years

21:43.903 --> 21:44.870 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
past.

21:44.904 --> 21:46.672 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

21:46.705 --> 21:47.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN NICHOLSON, U.S. Commander
in Afghanistan:
We're trying to build an
airplane while in

21:47.439 --> 21:48.741 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
flight, OK?

21:48.774 --> 21:50.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So they're fighting a war while
we're trying
to build an army.

21:50.910 --> 21:52.578 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This is very hard.

21:52.611 --> 21:57.383 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And when you look at the
histories of any
of our Western coalition force
members who

21:57.416 --> 22:01.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are here, they have had a
similar long journey
to build the professional armies
that we have

22:01.687 --> 22:03.622 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
today.

22:03.656 --> 22:08.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so this is primarily the
challenge, casualties,
the need to develop leaders, the
need to develop

22:08.661 --> 22:11.597 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
systems where none previously
existed.

22:11.630 --> 22:13.432 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, it does take time.

22:13.465 --> 22:18.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: Sergeant 1st
Class Philip
Nixon is serving a second tour
here.

22:18.470 --> 22:22.174 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In 2010, he was fighting in
Southern Afghanistan.

22:22.208 --> 22:27.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now he's the platoon leader of
the Guardian
Angels, a mix of U.S. and NATO
troops charged

22:27.613 --> 22:30.816 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with protection of the military
advisers and
their bases across the country.

22:30.849 --> 22:34.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SGT. 1ST CLASS PHILIP NIXON,
Guardian Angels:
Compared to when I was here in
Afghanistan

22:34.653 --> 22:40.693 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
six years ago, the Afghan army,
the ANA have
come a long way.

22:40.726 --> 22:44.330 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They are -- the facilities are
much better.

22:44.363 --> 22:47.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Their soldiers seem to be doing
a lot.

22:47.299 --> 22:55.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think what we're able to do
here with the
train, advise, and assist
mission has improved

22:55.608 --> 22:57.776 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
drastically from the last time I
was here.

22:57.810 --> 22:59.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: A lot has
changed in six
years.

23:00.012 --> 23:05.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. policy in Afghanistan
remains focused
on counterterrorism, but now
they're relying

23:05.551 --> 23:08.587 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the Afghans to execute most
of that mission.

23:08.621 --> 23:12.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
American troops on this base are
part of the
main mission of U.S. forces here
in Afghanistan

23:12.391 --> 23:15.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to train, advise and assist
Afghan security
forces.

23:15.961 --> 23:22.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's an Afghan base just next
door, and
there are bases like this all
over Afghanistan,

23:22.101 --> 23:27.506 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
like Shorabak in Helmand
Province, Southern
Afghanistan, where Afghan
trainers and U.S.

23:27.539 --> 23:32.378 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
advisers are putting the Afghan
215 Corps
through their paces.

23:32.411 --> 23:36.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
American and British forces left
Helmand in
2014.

23:36.248 --> 23:40.252 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
After the Taliban made
considerable gains
in the absence of coalition
forces, hundreds

23:40.286 --> 23:43.289 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of U.S. troops have returned.

23:43.322 --> 23:48.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, with new leaders in the
Afghan corps,
the coalition is teaching them
new tactics

23:48.560 --> 23:50.896 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to fight a resurgent Taliban.

23:50.929 --> 23:54.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Within the past year, the
Taliban briefly
captured Kunduz city in the
North this summer,

23:54.933 --> 24:00.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this summer besieged Lashkar Gah
in the south,
and this week threatened Tirin
Kot in Central

24:00.539 --> 24:01.573 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Afghanistan.

24:01.607 --> 24:03.375 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

24:03.409 --> 24:05.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN NICHOLSON: When you look at
the population
and district control, the
Afghans control

24:05.778 --> 24:11.116 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
about 68 percent of the
population and about
62 percent of the districts.

24:11.150 --> 24:17.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Taliban control about 10
percent of the
population and 10 percent of the
districts;

24:17.256 --> 24:19.525 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
25 percent of the country is
contested.

24:19.558 --> 24:20.859 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's in play.

24:20.893 --> 24:23.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: And the fight
isn't just
on the battlefields.

24:23.329 --> 24:25.564 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Taliban strikes wherever it
can.

24:25.597 --> 24:27.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Just behind me is the Ministry
of Defense.

24:27.766 --> 24:32.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A few minutes ago, there were
two explosions,
the police and security forces,
you can see,

24:32.137 --> 24:33.305 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
out in full force.

24:33.339 --> 24:34.473 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're moving the people back.

24:34.506 --> 24:37.042 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is a very busy market area.

24:37.076 --> 24:41.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it is one of the busiest
parts of the
day, as businesses let out, as
offices let

24:41.747 --> 24:43.549 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
out, so the streets were very,
very full.

24:43.582 --> 24:47.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The police say some suspicious
men went over
there, so they're moving
everybody as far

24:47.786 --> 24:49.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
back as they can.

24:49.288 --> 24:53.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is the kind of security
problem that
Afghans face on a daily basis.

24:54.026 --> 24:57.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This Taliban attack in Kabul was
particularly
brutal and deadly.

24:57.429 --> 24:59.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
First, a remote-controlled bomb
went off.

24:59.832 --> 25:06.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then, as help arrived for the
wounded, a suicide
bomber dressed in an Afghan army
uniform detonated

25:06.338 --> 25:08.474 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
himself in the crowd of helpers.

25:08.507 --> 25:14.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At least 35 people were killed,
including
an army general and three senior
police officers.

25:14.046 --> 25:15.981 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
More than 90 were wounded.

25:16.014 --> 25:18.517 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the Taliban aren't the only
threat in
Afghanistan.

25:18.550 --> 25:20.386 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GEN.

25:20.419 --> 25:24.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN NICHOLSON: Of the 60
designated terrorist
organizations that the U.S. has
identified,

25:24.323 --> 25:27.226 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
10 of them reside in this
region.

25:27.259 --> 25:31.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, our presence here enables us
to keep pressure
on those organizations and
prevent another

25:31.764 --> 25:33.232 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
9/11.

25:33.265 --> 25:36.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: Both al-Qaida
and the Islamic
State are in Afghanistan.

25:36.335 --> 25:41.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. commander got expanded
authorities
this year to fight both ISIS and
the Taliban

25:41.273 --> 25:42.741 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
directly.

25:42.775 --> 25:46.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, again, U.S. forces are
fighting here,
supported by American planes.

25:46.779 --> 25:49.915 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the Afghans remain on the
front line.

25:49.948 --> 25:56.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have a new air force, but
it will take
years before its at full
strength and capacity,

25:56.188 --> 26:00.759 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and Afghan ground forces
continue to take
punishing casualties.

26:00.793 --> 26:05.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Last year, more than 5,500 died
and 14,000
were wounded.

26:05.998 --> 26:11.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Casualties this year are up an
estimated 20
percent, the price of defending
a country

26:11.103 --> 26:13.806 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they got back from the Taliban
15 years ago.

26:13.839 --> 26:20.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Jennifer Glasse
in Kabul.

26:20.579 --> 26:28.620 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

26:28.654 --> 26:34.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
what the 9/11
memorials mean to victims'
families in their

26:34.393 --> 26:35.894 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
own words.

26:35.928 --> 26:39.498 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, first: the analysis of
Shields and Brooks.

26:39.531 --> 26:44.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's syndicated columnist Mark
Shields and
New York Times columnist David
Brooks.

26:44.670 --> 26:45.637 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to you both.

26:45.671 --> 26:47.906 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's good to see you again.

26:47.940 --> 26:50.142 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Let's talk about the
presidential campaign.

26:50.175 --> 26:55.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
David, we saw the two candidates
together
at the same place this week, but
not at the

26:55.314 --> 26:59.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
same time, at this televised
forum that NBC
sponsored.

26:59.451 --> 27:02.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What did you make of it, of
their performance
and what they had to say?

27:02.387 --> 27:04.256 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: I thought they
both lost.

27:04.289 --> 27:05.724 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I thought America lost.

27:05.757 --> 27:06.692 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Humanity lost.

27:06.725 --> 27:08.694 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
A little piece of my soul died.

27:08.727 --> 27:09.695 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I thought they...

27:09.728 --> 27:10.729 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: That bad?

27:10.762 --> 27:12.564 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: I thought they
both did poorly.

27:12.598 --> 27:18.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I thought she was evasive and
cross and looked
like she was imperious and was
angry to be

27:18.937 --> 27:20.639 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
challenged.

27:20.672 --> 27:25.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She had plenty of information,
but not a lot
of relatability and not a lot of
humanity

27:25.444 --> 27:27.713 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and not a lot of vision for
foreign policy.

27:27.746 --> 27:30.516 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He, if anything, was a little
worse.

27:30.549 --> 27:34.820 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He is, and as he has wont to do,
said about
six ridiculous things.

27:34.853 --> 27:36.722 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The admiration for Putin is of
long standing.

27:36.755 --> 27:41.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But to me, the thing that really
made me think
was his claim that in Iraq we
should have

27:41.627 --> 27:44.062 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
left a core of people to take
the oil.

27:44.096 --> 27:49.735 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, that is -- first of all,
it's impractical,
but it's also moral idiocy.

27:49.768 --> 27:52.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Maybe you're selfish and you
think, oh, I
got some oil and I got some
guns, I should

27:52.738 --> 27:54.540 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
take it.

27:54.573 --> 27:58.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if you go through any realm
of education,
which is what we try to do with
people, you

27:58.076 --> 28:01.280 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
learn that that's called
imperialism, that's
called plunder.

28:01.313 --> 28:02.481 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's morally wrong.

28:02.514 --> 28:04.316 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It ruins your credibility.

28:04.349 --> 28:08.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The idea that a big country is
going to go
out and send troops into some
country to take

28:08.453 --> 28:12.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their resources, and then the
rest of the
world is going to somehow trust
us is just

28:12.491 --> 28:14.226 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a ridiculous notion.

28:14.259 --> 28:18.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so he says things that are
just plainly
ridiculous.

28:18.196 --> 28:20.265 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But -- so that's why was so
depressed.

28:20.299 --> 28:22.000 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

28:22.034 --> 28:25.437 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Mark,
humanity lost as
a result of this encounter or
this performance

28:25.470 --> 28:26.672 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this week?

28:26.705 --> 28:27.906 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

28:27.940 --> 28:31.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Judy, I wasn't --
it wasn't
Lincoln-Douglas.

28:31.476 --> 28:33.345 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

28:33.378 --> 28:38.183 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: And most
importantly of all,
I think David's point about the
oil is well-taken.

28:38.216 --> 28:42.888 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think it's valid and I think
it's true.

28:42.921 --> 28:45.857 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That is not the United States.

28:45.891 --> 28:47.092 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That is pillaging.

28:47.125 --> 28:51.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is the worst form of
imperialism that
he's describing.

28:51.063 --> 28:56.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It would mean leaving thousands
of Americans
there to protect the oil
drilling.

28:56.201 --> 29:03.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, it just is -- it's
indefensible on
logistical, moral and political
grounds.

29:03.141 --> 29:06.678 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But that aside, I think what it
did -- and
you have moderated debates.

29:06.712 --> 29:09.247 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have never moderated a debate,
Judy, for
good reason.

29:09.281 --> 29:15.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think it's raised this --
Wednesday
night, partially because of the
unflattering

29:15.420 --> 29:21.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
press reaction to Matt Lauer's
performance,
has raised the stakes for the
moderator, who

29:21.827 --> 29:29.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is now put on notice, all of
them, that they
are not entitled in 2016 to sit
there while

29:30.002 --> 29:37.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
somebody makes a statement that
is factually
untrue and is -- can be proven
false, as Mr.

29:37.409 --> 29:43.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump did when he, in fact, said
that he had
always opposed the United
States' war in Iraq.

29:43.949 --> 29:47.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I just think that -- it's
tough to be
a moderator.

29:47.119 --> 29:53.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think that, given this
campaign and
the questions about the
integrity and honesty

29:53.091 --> 29:56.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the candidates, and the great
doubts about
them, I think that is now part
of the job

29:56.928 --> 29:58.630 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
description.

29:58.664 --> 30:00.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you see
that question
about the role of the moderator,
David?

30:00.132 --> 30:01.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes.

30:01.600 --> 30:03.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I watched the debate, and I
didn't think Matt
Lauer did that terribly.

30:03.435 --> 30:06.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I thought a lot of people who
were Clinton
partisans saw that she did bad,
and they decided

30:06.171 --> 30:09.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to blame him, which is what
normally happens
when one candidate does badly.

30:09.708 --> 30:13.245 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
As for the role of the
moderator, I guess
I would say in moderation.

30:13.278 --> 30:16.848 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If the moderator corrects a fact
or two, that
would be fine.

30:16.882 --> 30:21.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If it turns into an argument
between the moderator
and the candidate, that is not
what we want.

30:21.420 --> 30:25.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the final point to be made,
just in terms
of cognitive science, the idea
that when you

30:25.390 --> 30:30.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
correct a fact, you erase that
fact from people's
memories is the reverse of the
truth.

