acres, it would
have actually have been a
terrible mistake,

47:13.364 --> 47:18.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because it would have carved a
huge hole in
the heart of America's largest
city.

47:18.969 --> 47:23.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And restoring the life of the
city was an
important part of the mission.

47:23.607 --> 47:28.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JIM LAYCHAK, President, Pentagon
Memorial
Fund: I view the memorial as a
place that

47:28.212 --> 47:29.980 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
family members can come.

47:30.014 --> 47:35.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whenever they need to reflect or
gain some
hope or some renewal, they can
come any time.

47:35.386 --> 47:36.821 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
My name is Jim Laychak.

47:36.854 --> 47:38.723 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm president of the Pentagon
Memorial Fund.

47:38.756 --> 47:42.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I lost my brother Dave here
in the Pentagon
on 9/11.

47:42.293 --> 47:43.494 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I think about Dave a lot.

47:43.527 --> 47:46.564 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I don't have to be somewhere
to think
of him.

47:46.597 --> 47:51.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A song will come on, or I will
see my kids
or his kids doing something that
reminds me

47:51.368 --> 47:56.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of him, or I will have a memory
of something
when we were growing up that
helped me remember

47:56.607 --> 47:58.342 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
him.

47:58.375 --> 48:02.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think this is more for
those who lost
friends here and really need it
when they

48:02.646 --> 48:04.415 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
need it.

48:04.448 --> 48:07.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: Last year, we went to New
York and saw
the 9/11 memorial for the first
time, so we

48:07.985 --> 48:13.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
felt that we needed to come here
to almost
complete the journey to see
exactly what happened

48:13.224 --> 48:14.925 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
here.

48:14.959 --> 48:16.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHILIP KENNICOTT, The Washington
Post: It
was a challenge to make in some
ways, because

48:16.861 --> 48:21.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it included both people who were
at the Pentagon,
including military personnel,
and people who

48:21.432 --> 48:23.701 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were civilians on the plane who
died.

48:23.734 --> 48:27.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so they had to look for a
way to memorialize
both groups of people.

48:27.671 --> 48:30.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JIM LAYCHAK: I'm actually
sitting on my brother
Dave's bench.

48:30.941 --> 48:38.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the significance of it for
me is that
it's on 1961 age line, the year
that Dave

48:38.149 --> 48:39.884 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was born.

48:39.917 --> 48:43.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you come up to the bench,
and you read
his name, you will see the
Pentagon in the

48:43.220 --> 48:46.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
background, which signifies that
he was working
in the Pentagon.

48:46.557 --> 48:51.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GORDON FELT: The plane that went
down at Shanksville
had passengers on it who
actually resisted.

48:51.729 --> 48:53.130 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They chose to act.

48:53.164 --> 48:54.999 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They fought back.

48:55.032 --> 49:01.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They breached the cockpit and
fought for control
of that flight, and in doing so,
they saved

49:01.105 --> 49:04.875 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
countless other lives and they
perhaps saved
the Capitol Building.

49:04.909 --> 49:10.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PHILIP KENNICOTT: It was one of
the very powerful
moments of 9/11, because it was
perhaps the

49:10.080 --> 49:14.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
only moment in that day in which
the terrorists
weren't writing the narrative.

49:14.318 --> 49:18.255 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so the passengers on that
plane are remembered
quite heroically.

49:18.289 --> 49:22.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And yet I think, very much to
the credit of
the design of Shanksville, it's
not a bombastic

49:22.760 --> 49:24.495 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
memorial.

49:24.528 --> 49:29.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not about exaggerating the
importance
of that heroism, as important
that it is.

49:29.166 --> 49:35.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's really about the loss of
the people and
a sense, truly a sense of
healing, more than

49:35.406 --> 49:37.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
most of the memorials, because
it's in a rural
landscape.

49:37.408 --> 49:39.677 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEN NACKE, Brother of September
11 Victim:
This is where my brother is.

49:39.710 --> 49:46.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is where I choose to
remember his last
moments on this world and talk
to him, tell

49:46.884 --> 49:52.790 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
him, you know, how proud -- you
know, that
he's missed and that he's loved.

49:52.823 --> 49:57.061 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PHILIP KENNICOTT: What's
happened, I think,
is the natural progression, as
the event recedes

49:57.094 --> 50:01.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
farther into history, there is a
tendency
to divide those people who were
personally

50:01.632 --> 50:07.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
connected from the events from
the rest of
us who remember them now
increasingly as historical

50:07.071 --> 50:09.006 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
events.

50:09.039 --> 50:13.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You see people who wander
through, who look,
who are looking at it as an
object, as a historical

50:14.011 --> 50:15.813 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
marker.

